James Mullan, 52, with Desmond the horse, at his stables beside the border with County Derry, in Northern Ireland, and County Donegal in the Republic of Ireland. “I grew up seeing the Battle of the Bogside, Bloody Sunday, and Ireland now is in a lot better position,” he said. “Everybody’s got to compromise a bit, but at the end of the day we’re all here for a short while. That hill and mountain that we’re looking at there is going to be there long after all of us.”
The Bogside neighborhood of County Derry was the scene of riots in 1969.
Jeanette Warke, project manager of a youth club in the Fountain Estate, a neighborhood in County Derry. “I remember my mum pushing my younger brother in the pram. It was a large pram with a false bottom in it and she always got butter and cigarettes,” she said. “Actually they were smuggled, let’s say, but I think that was the excitement in it you know, and she lifted my brother out and then lifted this panel and this curved bit then the stuff went into it.”
 
Daniel Pritchard, 17, at a youth club in the Fountain Estate in County Derry. “It’s got a lot better,” he said. “The bitterness is still here like. It’s never going to go. Never.”
 
Lewis Atkinson, 17, outside the youth club. He said the Republic of Ireland is “good, it’s just different to here. There are Irish words, and you can tell that you’re not here, you’re just past the border ... they don’t care about religion, where you’re from, or the way you speak, the way you dress.”
